). This species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[897,965,882,908]" name="Brazil" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[192,1440,925,986]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,925,951]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[557,665,925,951]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macilenta">
<emphasis box="[557,665,925,951]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">macilenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin adjective derived from 
<emphasis box="[1041,1109,926,951]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">macer</emphasis>
(= thin). I refer to the narrow body form of this beetle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
